[1] Ethiopia
Date: Mon 11 Aug 2014
Source: UN Office for the Coordination of the Humanitarian Affairs, Ethiopia Weekly Humanitarian Bulletin [edited]
http://reliefweb.int/report/ethiopia/ethiopia-weekly-humanitarian-bulletin-11-august-2014


In the 1st week of August 2014, 160 suspected measles cases were reported nationwide. 50 per cent were reported from the Amhara and Oromia regions. In 2014, the Government and its partners responded to 202 measles outbreaks across 189 woredas [an administrative sub-division, see below]. The majority were in Amhara (61 outbreaks), Oromia (75 outbreaks) and SNNP (31 outbreaks) regions. 69 per cent of the confirmed cases were children under 15 years old.

--
Communicated by:
Dr Ota
JICA Amhara Region Infectious Disease Surveillance Project
<otam@jata.or.jp>

[ProMED-mail thanks Dr Ota for extracting this information on our behalf. It would be useful to be able to relate this information to the current extent of measles vaccination throughout Ethiopia.

The Administrative Divisions of Ethiopia comprise 9 regions and 2 city-regions (Addis Ababa and Dire Dawa). Regions are divided into zones (this level has been abolished in most regions), Woredas (districts, and city areas) and Kebeles (municipalities, suburbs). Districts or Woredas are the 3rd-level administrative divisions of Ethiopia. They are composed of a number of wards (kebele) or neighborhood associations, which are the smallest unit of local government in Ethiopia.

A description of the social history of Ethiopia and accompanying map can be accessed at: http://unpan1.un.org/intradoc/groups/public/docuanments/un/unpan023264.pdf. - Mod.CP]

[A ProMED-mail HealthMap is available at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2698339,95.]

