[5] Australia (Tasmania)
Date: Wed 13 Aug 2014
Source: The Examiner [abridged, edited]
http://www.examiner.com.au/story/2483987/tasmanian-measles-cases-rise/?cs=12


Measles has continued to spread after 3 travellers brought the disease into Tasmania in the past month. The Population Health Services' senior medical adviser said there had been 6 confirmed cases and 2 suspected cases of measles in Tasmania since the start of July [2014]. They are the 1st cases of measles in the state since 2009. The medical adviser said 3 of the infections were caught overseas or interstate, and the remaining 5 were caught in Tasmania through close contact with the known cases.

"Further cases of measles arising from the last of these recent cases remain possible for a few more days,'' according to the adviser. ''Information has been provided to people who may have had contact with recent cases so they can remain alert to measles symptoms."

Dr Veitch said the measles vaccine was recommended for children at the age of 12 months, with a 2nd dose at 18 months. He said anyone younger than 49 who was not sure they had received 2 doses of measles-containing vaccine should discuss getting a booster from their GP.

[Byline: Jodie Stephens]

--
